{
  "What is a scientific model?": "",
  "A representation of an object, system, or process that helps explain or predict": "",
  "An exact copy of a real object that is identical in every single detail possible": "",
  "A proven scientific fact that has been confirmed through controlled experiments": "",
  "A guess about how something works that does not need any evidence to support": "",
  "A scientific model is a simplified representation of something complex — an object, system, or process — that helps scientists explain observations, make predictions, and communicate ideas.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of a physical model?": "",
  "A mathematical equation describing gravity": "",
  "A 3D model of the solar system made from balls and wire": "",
  "A computer program that simulates weather patterns": "",
  "A written description of how volcanoes erupt in nature": "",
  "A physical model is a tangible, three-dimensional object you can touch. A solar system model made from balls and wire is a classic example. It helps visualize the relative positions of planets.": "",
  "What is a mathematical model?": "",
  "A 3D object that you can hold and physically manipulate": "",
  "An equation or formula that represents a relationship between variables": "",
  "A drawing or diagram that shows the parts of a system visually": "",
  "A verbal explanation of a scientific concept given during class": "",
  "A mathematical model uses equations, formulas, or calculations to describe relationships. For example, F = ma (force equals mass times acceleration) is a mathematical model of how force works.": "",
  "Why are scientific models useful?": "",
  "They help explain, visualize, and predict things that may be too complex or large": "",
  "They replace the need for any experiments or observations in science entirely": "",
  "They always represent reality with 100% perfect accuracy and complete detail": "",
  "They are only used for educational purposes and never for real science work": "",
  "Models help scientists understand and communicate concepts that are too small (atoms), too large (galaxies), too fast (light), too slow (evolution), or too dangerous (nuclear reactions) to study directly.": "",
  "What is a limitation of all scientific models?": "",
  "They are simplified and cannot show every detail of the real thing": "",
  "They are always wrong and never useful for any purpose in science": "",
  "They can only be created by professional scientists at universities": "",
  "They cannot be updated or changed once they have been created": "",
  "All models are simplifications of reality and have limitations. They cannot include every detail. For example, a globe does not show every building, and an atom model does not show exact electron positions.": "",
  "A globe is a model of what?": "",
  "The Sun": "",
  "Earth": "",
  "The Moon": "",
  "A country": "",
  "A globe is a physical model of Earth. It shows the shape, continents, and oceans at a reduced scale. However, it is simplified — it cannot show individual mountains, buildings, or people.": "",
  "When should a scientific model be revised?": "",
  "Never, because once a model is made it should stay the same forever": "",
  "When new evidence or data shows that the model is incomplete or inaccurate": "",
  "Only when a completely new scientist takes over the research project": "",
  "Every year on a fixed schedule, regardless of whether new data exists": "",
  "Scientific models should be revised whenever new evidence shows the current model is incomplete or incorrect. The history of the atom model shows how models evolve as understanding improves.": "",
  "Which of the following is a conceptual model?": "",
  "A diagram showing the water cycle with arrows and labels": "",
  "A clay sculpture of a human skeleton on display in class": "",
  "The equation E = mc² written in a physics textbook page": "",
  "A plastic model of a DNA double helix placed on a desk": "",
  "A conceptual model uses diagrams, flowcharts, or descriptions to represent ideas and relationships. A water cycle diagram with arrows showing evaporation, condensation, and precipitation is a conceptual model.": "",
  "How has the model of the atom changed over time?": "",
  "It has not changed; scientists have always agreed on the same atom model": "",
  "It has evolved from simple solid spheres to complex cloud-like electron models": "",
  "It has become simpler over time as scientists removed unnecessary details": "",
  "It was perfected by the first scientist and has never needed any changes": "",
  "The atom model has evolved significantly: from Dalton's solid sphere, to Thomson's plum pudding model, to Rutherford's nuclear model, to Bohr's orbital model, to the modern electron cloud model. Each revision came from new evidence.": "",
  "What type of model is a computer simulation of a car crash?": "",
  "A physical model": "",
  "A conceptual model": "",
  "A computer model": "",
  "A mental model": "",
  "A computer simulation of a car crash is a computer model. It uses mathematical equations and programming to simulate real-world physics, allowing engineers to test safety features without destroying real cars.": "",
  "What is a physical model in science?": "",
  "A three-dimensional object that you can touch and that represents a real thing": "",
  "A set of mathematical equations used to describe a natural process in detail": "",
  "A diagram drawn on paper that shows relationships between different ideas": "",
  "A computer program that uses code to simulate events that happen in nature": "",
  "A physical model is a tangible, 3D representation of an object or system. Examples include a model of the solar system, a model volcano, or a model of a cell. They can be held and examined from different angles.": "",
  "What is a conceptual model?": "",
  "A diagram, flowchart, or description that represents ideas and relationships": "",
  "A tangible object that can be held in your hands and physically examined": "",
  "A computer program that runs mathematical simulations using real data": "",
  "An equation that calculates the exact value of a scientific measurement": "",
  "A conceptual model uses visual representations like diagrams, flowcharts, or maps to explain ideas and show relationships. The food web, water cycle, and plate tectonics diagrams are all conceptual models.": "",
  "What does 'scale model' mean?": "",
  "A model built to a specific ratio of the actual size of the real object": "",
  "A model that is always exactly the same size as the object it represents": "",
  "A model that weighs the same as the real object it is meant to represent": "",
  "A model that shows only the weight or mass of the object it represents": "",
  "A scale model is a physical model built proportionally larger or smaller than the real object. For example, a 1:100 scale model of a building means every dimension is 1/100th of the real size.": "",
  "What does 'computer model' mean in science?": "",
  "A program that uses math and data to simulate real-world processes digitally": "",
  "A physical model of a computer built from clay or plastic for display purposes": "",
  "Any photograph or picture that is stored on a computer's hard drive system": "",
  "A computer that is used to type up lab reports after experiments are completed": "",
  "A computer model is a software program that uses mathematical equations and data to simulate real-world processes. Weather forecasting, climate prediction, and flight simulation all use computer models.": "",
  "What does 'analogy' mean when used in scientific models?": "",
  "Comparing a complex concept to something familiar to help explain how it works": "",
  "Making an exact copy of a scientific instrument for use in a different lab": "",
  "Measuring the size of a model compared to the size of the real-world object": "",
  "Using numbers and equations to predict the outcome of an experiment test": "",
  "An analogy compares an unfamiliar concept to something more familiar. For example, comparing an atom's electrons orbiting the nucleus to planets orbiting the Sun is an analogy that helps understanding.": "",
  "What does it mean to say a model is 'simplified'?": "",
  "The model leaves out some details to focus on the most important features": "",
  "The model is incorrect and should not be used by scientists or students": "",
  "The model includes every possible detail about the object or system shown": "",
  "The model was created quickly without any thought about its accuracy at all": "",
  "A simplified model intentionally omits less important details to focus on key features. This makes complex systems easier to understand. All models are simplified to some degree.": "",
  "What does 'representation' mean in the context of scientific models?": "",
  "Something that stands for or depicts another thing in a simplified way": "",
  "An exact duplicate that is identical to the original in every measurable way": "",
  "A written report that describes the results of a scientific experiment": "",
  "A type of scientific instrument used to measure quantities in a laboratory": "",
  "A representation is something that stands for or depicts something else. Scientific models are representations — they stand for real objects, systems, or processes but are not the actual things themselves.": "",
  "What does 'prediction' mean in the context of scientific models?": "",
  "Using a model to forecast what will happen under specific conditions": "",
  "Describing what happened during an experiment after it has been completed": "",
  "Building a physical model using materials found in a classroom setting": "",
  "Recording the observations made during a field study in the outdoors": "",
  "One key use of scientific models is making predictions about future events or untested conditions. Weather models predict storms, climate models forecast temperature changes, and physics models predict motion.": "",
  "What does 'accuracy of a model' mean?": "",
  "How well the model's predictions match real-world observations and data": "",
  "How expensive the model was to build using laboratory equipment and materials": "",
  "How large or small the physical model is compared to the original object": "",
  "How long it took the scientist to create and test the model in the lab": "",
  "The accuracy of a model refers to how well it matches reality. An accurate weather model successfully predicts actual weather. An inaccurate model would fail to match real-world observations.": "",
  "What does 'limitation' mean when discussing scientific models?": "",
  "A way in which the model fails to perfectly represent the real thing": "",
  "The maximum number of times a model can be used before it breaks": "",
  "The total cost required to build the model from available materials": "",
  "The number of scientists required to work on the model at one time": "",
  "A limitation is an aspect where the model does not accurately represent reality. All models have limitations because they are simplifications. Identifying limitations helps scientists understand what the model can and cannot tell them.": "",
  "A student builds a model of the solar system using different-sized balls on sticks. The balls are correctly sized relative to each other, but the distances between them are not to scale. What is a limitation of this model?": "",
  "The colors of the balls do not match the actual colors of the planets": "",
  "The distances between planets are not accurately represented to scale": "",
  "The model uses balls instead of actual planets orbiting the Sun": "",
  "The model cannot be taken outdoors and shown to other classrooms": "",
  "The inaccurate distances are a significant limitation because they give a misleading impression of how far apart the planets are. In reality, the spaces between planets are enormous compared to their sizes.": "",
  "A scientist uses a computer model to predict how a forest fire will spread. The model shows the fire moving east, but the actual fire moves north. What should the scientist do?": "",
  "Conclude that computer models are completely useless for predicting fires": "",
  "Revise the model by adding better data about wind patterns and terrain": "",
  "Ignore the real fire data and trust the computer model's prediction only": "",
  "Abandon all fire research since the prediction did not match the result": "",
  "When a model does not match reality, it should be revised with better data. The scientist might need to add more accurate wind data, terrain information, or vegetation data to improve the model's predictions.": "",
  "A teacher explains that an atom is like a tiny solar system, with electrons orbiting the nucleus like planets orbit the Sun. What type of model is the teacher using?": "",
  "A physical model that can be held in your hands": "",
  "A mathematical model using equations and formulas": "",
  "An analogy model comparing atoms to a familiar system": "",
  "A computer simulation running on laboratory software": "",
  "The teacher is using an analogy — comparing the atom to the solar system to make the unfamiliar concept easier to understand. While helpful, this analogy has limitations because electrons do not orbit in neat paths like planets.": "",
  "An architect builds a small-scale model of a new building before construction begins. The model is 1/50th the size of the real building. Why is this model useful?": "",
  "It allows the architect to live inside the model and test the building": "",
  "It lets the architect and clients visualize the design before spending money to build it": "",
  "It guarantees the real building will look exactly like the model in every detail": "",
  "It is not useful; the architect should just build the real building directly": "",
  "A scale model allows the architect and clients to see and evaluate the design, identify problems, and make changes before spending millions on actual construction. It is much cheaper to modify a model than a real building.": "",
  "A student says, 'My model of a cell is perfect because it shows all the organelles.' Why is this statement incorrect?": "",
  "Because cell models should never include organelles in them at all": "",
  "Because no model is perfect; it lacks details like molecular processes inside each organelle": "",
  "Because the student did not use the correct colors for each organelle in the model": "",
  "Because only computer models can show organelles, not physical models of any kind": "",
  "No model is perfect. Even if it shows all organelles, it cannot show the thousands of chemical reactions occurring inside each organelle, the actual scale, or the dynamic movement of molecules.": "",
  "Scientists in the 1800s modeled the atom as a solid sphere. Later, they discovered atoms have internal structure. How did this affect the model?": "",
  "The solid sphere model was kept because changing models is not allowed in science": "",
  "The model was revised to include a nucleus, protons, neutrons, and electrons": "",
  "Scientists decided that atoms do not actually exist and stopped studying them": "",
  "The new evidence was ignored because the old model was simpler and easier": "",
  "As new evidence was discovered, the atom model was revised multiple times. This demonstrates that scientific models are not permanent — they evolve as understanding improves through new evidence.": "",
  "A flight simulator allows pilots to practice flying without leaving the ground. What type of model is a flight simulator?": "",
  "A purely conceptual model showing flight diagrams on paper only": "",
  "A computer-based simulation model that recreates real flight conditions": "",
  "A scale model of an airplane that sits on a shelf for display purposes": "",
  "A mathematical model consisting only of equations and formulas on paper": "",
  "A flight simulator is a computer-based model that recreates flight conditions including weather, turbulence, and instrument readings. It allows safe, repeatable practice without the risks and costs of actual flying.": "",
  "A student creates a model of the water cycle on a poster. She includes evaporation, condensation, and precipitation. Her teacher says the model is missing the step of infiltration (water soaking into ground). What does this teach about models?": "",
  "Models are useless if they are missing even a single component of the system": "",
  "Models can always be improved by adding details that were initially left out": "",
  "The water cycle does not actually include infiltration as a real process step": "",
  "Models should never be changed once they have been created and presented": "",
  "Models can always be improved by adding more detail or correcting inaccuracies. The student's initial model was useful but incomplete. Adding infiltration makes it a more comprehensive representation of the water cycle.": "",
  "A toy car is used to demonstrate how friction affects motion. The toy car is much simpler than a real car. Why can it still be a useful model?": "",
  "It cannot be useful because it is not the same size as a real car at all": "",
  "It demonstrates the basic principles of friction even though it is simplified": "",
  "It is only useful for entertainment purposes and not for learning science": "",
  "It proves that friction works differently on small objects than large objects": "",
  "Even though a toy car is simplified, it still demonstrates the basic physics of friction. A model does not need to be perfectly realistic to effectively illustrate a scientific concept.": "",
  "A group of students debates whether a diagram of the food chain or a 3D diorama is a better model of an ecosystem. Which statement is most accurate?": "",
  "The diagram is always better because it shows relationships between organisms clearly": "",
  "The diorama is always better because it uses three-dimensional physical objects": "",
  "Both models are useful but emphasize different aspects of the ecosystem": "",
  "Neither model is useful because ecosystems are too complex to be modeled at all": "",
  "Both models have strengths. The diagram clearly shows feeding relationships (who eats whom), while the diorama shows the physical habitat and spatial arrangement. Different models serve different purposes.": ""
}